Wind energy is a form of renewable electricity generation that helps to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. 
Because of the variable nature of the wind resource, the ability to forecast wind speed some time ahead is valuable. The wind is sufficiently stable and predictable on an annual scale, although it presents significant variations at smaller timescales. The forecast of energy production allows to foresee possible variations in generation, making possible a better management of the electric network. In addition, flow modeling is useful for prospecting and installation of future projects.

%La energía eólica es una forma de generación eléctrica renovable que ayuda a disminuir las emisiones de gases de efecto invernadero al reemplazar fuentes de energía a base de combustibles fósiles. 
%El viento es suficientemente estable y predecible a escala anual, aunque presenta variaciones significativas a escalas de tiempo menores. El pronóstico de producción de energía permite prever posibles variaciones en la generación, posibilitando una mejor gestión de la red eléctrica. Además, el modelado del flujo resulta de utilidad para la prospección e instalación de futuros proyectos.


\end{posterbox}


\begin{posterbox}[name=wake,column=0,row=0, below=summary]{Wake}

A wind turbine is a device for extracting kinetic energy from the wind, its aerodynamic behaviour is modeled by the use of an $actuator$ $disc$. The actuator disc induces a velocity variation which must be superimposed on the free-stream velocity.
% Assuming that the affected mass of air remains separate from the rest of the air, a boundary surface can be drawn containing the affected air mass and this boundary can be extended forming a long stream-tube of circular cross section.
The air within the stream-tube slows down, but does not become compressed, making the cross-sectional area expand. As the air passes through the rotor disc, there is a drop in static pressure such that, on leaving, the air is below the atmospheric pressure level. The air then proceeds downstream with reduced speed and static pressure – this region of the flow is called the $wake$.
The rise in static pressure is at the expense of the kinetic energy and so causes a further slowing down of the wind. Thus, between the far upstream and far wake conditions, no change in static pressure exists but there is a reduction in kinetic energy.

\begin{center}
  \includegraphics[width=6cm, height=4cm]{stream_tube.jpg}
  \label{fig:figlabel}
\end{center}

% \begin{itemize}
% \item $\infty$: far upstream, $d$: at disc, $w$: far wake
% \end{itemize}

\end{posterbox}

\begin{posterbox}[name=computational_methods,column=0,below=wake, above=bottom]{Computational Methods}

\begin{itemize}
\item $Direct$ $Numerical$ $Simulation$ $(DNS)$: N–S equations are numerically solved. The whole range of spatial and temporal scales of the turbulence must be resolved in the computational mesh. 
\end{itemize} 

\begin{itemize}
\item $Turbulence$ $Models$: a model is constructed to predict the effects of turbulence. The governing equations of the flow are averaged (RANS) in order to focus on large-scale and non-fluctuating features. \begin{itemize}
\item $Large$ $Eddy$ $Simulation$: ignors the smallest length scales, which are the most computationally expensive to resolve, via low-pass filtering of the Navier–Stokes equations, removing small-scale information from the solution.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize} 


\begin{itemize}
\item $Analytical$ $Models$: a model is derived by applying conservation of mass and momentum and assuming a specific distribution for the velocity of the fluid.

\end{itemize}


%Al modelar la estela de una turbina, la alternativa para ahorrar recursos computacionales es utilizar modelos reducidos, en los cuales se sustituyen las aspas por fuerzas volumétricas con efecto equivalente. 

\end{posterbox}


\begin{posterbox}[name=comparing_methods,column=1,below=wind_energy]{Comparing Methods}

Depending on the accuracy required in the study of a fluid, different computational methods are chosen. 

A DNS requires a number of mesh points $N$ satisfying $N^{3}\geq \mathrm {Re} ^{2.25}$, where $Re$ is the Reynolds number. Hence, the memory storage requirement in a DNS grows very fast with $Re$. For $Re$ encountered in most industrial applications, the computational resources required by a DNS exceed the capacity of the most powerful computers currently available.

For the simulation of practical engineering systems with complex geometry or flow configurations, LES has become increasingly sophisticated and accurate in recent years. It is cheaper than DNS but it still requires huge processing time.

When modelling wind farms to make power forecasting, it is important to reduce the time taken to run the simulation. This is the reason why simple analytical models are useful tools to predict wind-turbine wake flows. They are widely used due to their simplicity and low computational cost.


\begin{center}
  \includegraphics[width=6cm, height=3cm]{potencial_eolico_mundial}
  \label{fig:figlabel}
\end{center}


\end{posterbox}


\begin{posterbox}[name=analytical_models,column=1,below=comparing_methods,above=bottom]{Analytical Models}

%Se han propuesto diversos modelos de orden reducido para el estudio de la estela de una turbina. 

The pioneering analytical wake models were the ones proposed by $Jensen$ and $Frandsen$, they were presented more than 30 years ago, yet they continue to be a standard tool in commercial software packages. Both models assume a top-hat shape for the velocity deficit in the wake. They claimed that it gives an estimate of the energy content rather than describing the velocity field accurately. Nevertheless, note that the energy available in the wind varies as the cube of the wind speed and, therefore, an improper evaluation of velocity field in a wind farm can lead to large errors in the prediction of the energy output.


A new model was derived by Porté-Agel, applying conservation of mass and momentum and assuming a Gaussian distribution for the velocity deficit in the wake.

\end{posterbox}



\begin{posterbox}[name=equations,column=2,below=wind_energy]{Equations}
\begin{itemize}
\item Jensen
\begin{equation*}
\frac{\Delta U}{U_{\infty}} = \frac{1 - \sqrt{1 - C_T}}{(1 + \frac{2 k_{wake} x}{d_0})^2}
\end{equation*}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Frandsen
\begin{equation*}
\frac{\Delta U}{U_{\infty}} = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{2}\sqrt{1 - 2 \frac{A_0}{A_W(x)}C_T}
\end{equation*}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Porté-Agel
\begin{equation*}
\frac{\Delta U}{U_{\infty}} = C(x) exp\Bigg\{\frac{-1}{2(\frac{k^*x}{d_0} + \epsilon)^2}\bigg( \bigg( \frac{r(x,y)}{d_0}\bigg)^2\Bigg\}
\end{equation*}
\end{itemize}
Profiles of the mean velocity (top) and velocity deficit (bottom) downwind of a wind turbine obtained by assuming: (left) a top-hat and (right) a Gaussian distribution for the velocity deficit.
\begin{center}
  \includegraphics[width=6cm, height=4cm]{models.jpg}
  \label{fig:figlabel}
\end{center}
\end{posterbox}




